parts:
Short answer: it’s not your image. Your CSS is almost there—the left column (media) and the right column (text card) use the same min-height, but only the media column is set to explicitly fill the grid track height. Add two tiny rules so the **text card also fills the row** and both sides use **border-box sizing** (so borders/padding don’t throw off the math). If you want pixel-perfect parity on every browser, give the media a 1px transparent border to match the text card’s 1px border.

Add this to the end of `secondary-maths.css`:

```css
/* Make both columns use the same sizing model and fill the row */
.section--credentials .message-feature__media,
.section--credentials .message-feature__text {
  box-sizing: border-box;
  height: 100%;               /* ensures the grid item fills the track */
}

/* Media: match the text card’s border thickness to avoid a 1–2px optical mismatch */
.section--credentials .message-feature__media {
  border: 1px solid transparent;
}

/* Already present: same min-height on both sides and stretch alignment */
```

Why this fixes it:

- Your grid is already set to **align-items: stretch** and both columns share the same **min-height clamp** (260→380px) fileciteturn3file4L50-L57 fileciteturn3file4L59-L66 fileciteturn3file4L74-L84.  
- The image column (`.message-feature__media`) is set to `height: 100%`, but the text column isn’t, so some engines render the text card a hair shorter/taller than the stretched track. Making **both** columns `height: 100%` removes that drift.  
- A transparent 1px border on the media side cancels the visual difference from the text card’s real 1px border.

### About the image dimensions
Your `<img>` is already declared as **1200×900 (4:3)** with a 600×450 fallback via `<picture>`—that’s ideal for this layout and not the cause of the mismatch. Keep exactly that (1200×900 desktop; 600×450 smaller) and let `object-fit: cover` do the cropping inside the rounded frame fileciteturn3file1L6-L9 fileciteturn3file0L22-L26.

If you want a “belt-and-suspenders” *pixel-perfect* lockstep (even under extreme zoom levels), you can force an identical computed height on both sides:

```css
.section--credentials .message-feature { --feature-h: clamp(320px, 32vw, 420px); }
.section--credentials .message-feature__media,
.section--credentials .message-feature__text { height: var(--feature-h); min-height: 0; }
@media (max-width: 960px){
  .section--credentials .message-feature__media,
  .section--credentials .message-feature__text { height: auto; } /* revert on stacked view */
}
```

…but in most cases the first (lighter) patch is sufficient and keeps the text card flexible.
